name: app.R
content:
#library(CausalImpact)


# These are the necessary packages for R Shiny:
library(shiny)
library(bslib)
library(bsicons)
library(thematic)
library(plotly)
library(shinyjs)

library(ggplot2)
library(ggstatsplot)
library(patchwork)

#STAHP COMPLAINING D:
  options(warn=-1)

#Put the Base Data here:
set.seed(1)
x1 <- 100 + arima.sim(model = list(ar = 0.999), n = 100)
y <- 1.2 * x1 + rnorm(100)
y[71:100] <- y[71:100] + 300
data <- cbind(y, x1)


  
  
ui <- navbarPage(
#Similar to thematics, where you just initialize it and it works in the background
  useShinyjs(),
  
#Puts Title on the Application on the top
  title = "Causal Impact Demo in R Shiny",
  
  #Sets the theme for bslib using the Bootswatch Library:
  theme = bs_theme(
    bootswatch = "morph"
  ),
  
#Creates the sidebar
  sidebar = sidebar(
    title = "Demo Controls",
    fillable = TRUE,
    accordion_filters <- accordion(
      accordion_panel(
        "Intervention Effect", 
        icon = bs_icon("card-checklist"),
        
      #Setup with input funcs in Shiny are always input id, then the name in the app
      #followed by the values
        sliderInput("inv_mmt", 
                    "Intervention Moment", 
                    min = 4, 
                    max = 96, 
                    value = 70,
                    animate = animationOptions(
                      interval = 750,
                      loop = TRUE
                      )
                    ),
      #Switches between the interactive plots through plotly :)
        input_switch("plotly_switch", "Interactivity through Plotly",
                     value = TRUE)
      )
    )
  ),
  
# Creates a Tab
  tabsetPanel(
      id = "the_tabs",
    #Commented out because of incompatability with shinylive atm ;-;
      # tabPanel(
      #   title = "Causal Impact Base Graph",
      #   card(
      #     plotOutput("plot")
      #   ),
      # 
      # ),
    #Tab Panels referring to all the types of Plots
      tabPanel(
        title = "Comparing Periods (Base)",
        value = "tab1",
          card(
            full_screen = TRUE,
            
            conditionalPanel(
              full_screen = TRUE,
              condition = "input.plotly_switch == true",
              fillPage(
                plotlyOutput("plot2_plotly", height = "100%")
              )
            ),
            
            conditionalPanel(
              condition = "input.plotly_switch == false",
              plotOutput("plot2")
            )
            
          )
      ),
    
      tabPanel(
        title = "Comparing Periods (Images)",
        value = "tab2",
        card(
          imageOutput("magic_image", 
                      height = "100%")
        ),
      ),
    
      tabPanel(
        title = "Comparing Periods (Matrix)",
        value = "tab3",
        card(
          full_screen = TRUE,
          
          conditionalPanel(
            full_screen = TRUE,
            condition = "input.plotly_switch == true",
            plotlyOutput("mtx_plotly")
          ),
          
          conditionalPanel(
            condition = "input.plotly_switch == false",
            plotOutput("mtxplot")
          )
          
        )
      )

  ),

  

)

server <- function(input, output, session){
#Sets the Plots to the same theme as a bslib theme :D
  thematic_shiny()
  
#Kind of like a list of values to set that can by dynamically allocated
  v <- reactiveValues(
    lower_bound = 0,
    pre.period = 0,
    post.period = 0,
    df = 0
  )

#Tracks the Intervention Moment and updates the bounds accordingly
  observeEvent(input$inv_mmt,{
    v$lower_bound <- input$inv_mmt[1]
    v$pre.period <- c(1,v$lower_bound)
    v$post.period <- c(v$lower_bound+1,100)
    v$df <- data.frame(
      time = 1:nrow(data),
      y = data[, 1],
      period = ifelse(1:nrow(data) <= v$lower_bound, "1. Pre-intervention","2. Post-intervention")
      
    )
  })
  
#Looks complicated, just isn't
  observeEvent(input$the_tabs,{
  #Makes sure that the slider input is consistent with what is available for
  #each intervention moment in each tab
    if (input$the_tabs == "tab1"){
      updateSliderInput(session, "inv_mmt",
                        min = 4, 
                        max = 96, 
                        value = 70)
      shinyjs::show("plotly_switch")
    } else {
      updateSliderInput(session, "inv_mmt", 
                        min = 51,
                        max = 91,
                        value = 71)
    }
  #Gotta hide the switch for the "dark magics"
    if (input$the_tabs == "tab2"){
      shinyjs::hide("plotly_switch")
    }
    if (input$the_tabs == "tab3"){
      shinyjs::show("plotly_switch")
    }
    
  })

  # output$plot <- renderPlot({
  # #Scaling the Bounds of the Intervention Effect
  #   impact <- CausalImpact(data,v$pre.period, v$post.period)
  #   the_plot <- plot(impact, "pointwise") +
  #     geom_hline(yintercept = 10,
  #                col = 'red') +
  #     plot(impact, c("original", "cumulative"))
  # 
  #   plot(the_plot)
  # 
  # 
  # })

  
  
  
  output$plot2_plotly <- renderPlotly({
    ggbetweenstats(
      data = v$df,
      x = period,
      y = y,
      title = "Comparing the Pre and Post Intervention Periods",
      xlab = "Period",
      ylab = "Intervention Amounts",
      ggplot.component = list(theme(text = element_text(size = 14)))
    )
    #TODO: Add Fun Tooltip stuff!
    
    
  })
  
  output$plot2 <- renderPlot ({
    ggbetweenstats(
      data = v$df,
      x = period,
      y = y,
      title = "Comparing the Pre and Post Intervention Periods",
      xlab = "Period",
      ylab = "Intervention Amounts",
      ggplot.component = list(theme(text = element_text(size = 14)))
    )
  })

  output$magic_image <- renderImage({
  #Formatting the string so that it corresponds to the lower_bound number:
    imagename <- sprintf("www/Intervention%d.png", v$lower_bound)
  #Display the image without deleting them afterwards:
    list(src = imagename, 
         contentType = 'image/png',
         width = "100%",
         height = "75%")},
      deleteFile = FALSE
    )
  
  output$mtxplot <- renderPlot({
    will_data <- read.csv("Matrix1.csv")
    inv_adj_amt = v$lower_bound - 50
    yval = paste0("V", inv_adj_amt)
    #TODO: Fill this out soon...
    actual_data <- data.frame(time = 1:nrow(data), y = data[,1])
    p <- ggplot() + 
    geom_line(data = actual_data, aes(x = time, y = y), color = 'black', size = 1, linetype = "solid", name = "Actual Data") +
    geom_line(data = will_data, aes_string(x = "1:nrow(will_data)", y = yval), color = 'blue', size = 1, linetype = "dashed", name = "Predicted Data") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = v$lower_bound, color = "gray", linetype = "dashed", size = 1) +
    labs(title = 'Comparing the Pre and Post Intervention Periods',
         x = 'Time Period',
         y = 'Intervention Moments') + theme_minimal() + theme(plot.background =  element_rect(fill = "white"), legend.position = "bottom")
    plot(p)
    
  })
    
  output$mtx_plotly <- renderPlotly({
#Read the Matrix
  will_data <- read.csv("Matrix1.csv")
#Adjust the intervention amount based on the columns of the matrix
  inv_adj_amt <- v$lower_bound - 50
#Correspond it to the column of the matrix
  yval = paste0("V", inv_adj_amt)
  
  actual_data <- data.frame(time = 1:nrow(data), y = data[,1])
  
  fig <- plot_ly(x = actual_data$time, y = actual_data$y, type = 'scatter', mode = 'lines', 
                 name = "Actual Data", 
                 line = list(color = 'rgb(0,0,0)'))%>% 
    layout(title = 'Comparing the Pre and Post Intervention Periods',
           plot_bgcolor='#e5ecf6',  
           xaxis = list(  
             title = 'Time Period'),  
           yaxis = list(  
             title = 'Intervention Moments'),
           showlegend = TRUE,
         #Create a Vertical Line to indicate the intervention moment:
           shapes = list(
             list(
               type = "line",
               x0 = v$lower_bound, x1 = v$lower_bound,
               y0 = 0, y1 = 3500,
               line = list(color = "gray", width = 2, dash = 'dash')
             )
           ))
#Create a "Layer" to show the Predicted Data extrapolated from the matrix :)
  fig <- fig %>% add_trace(y = will_data[[yval]], name = 'Predicted Data', 
                           line = list(color = 'rgb(51,171,249)', dash = 'dash') 
                           )
  })
  }



shinyApp(ui,server)
